@Andrzej 

Andrzej, I’m curious about the popularity (or lack thereof) of jazz on Poland. I’ve been to your country 3 times: Once on an extended college-age European adventure not too long after Poland emerged from beyond the Iron Curtain, and twice for conferences in recent years. Each time I heard amazing jazz—live. (A snowy, frozen December night in Krakow comes to mind, in a jazz club in one of the ancient catacombs, with a fantastic quartet, enthusiastic audience, and awesome beer. Probably the best jazz experience I’ve ever had.)

Of course we seek out what we’re drawn to, so maybe jazz isn’t nearly as popular with the average Polish audience as my (limited) experience would indicate.

@Sam Lyons 

I'm not into jazz, and my parents weren't, either. I don't know anybody who prefers jazz to other genres, in fact. Still, I have heard about Polish jazz and I know it's supposed to be good. That does not have translate into it being popular though, and in my experience, it indeed does not. It may have been different before 1989, when Western music had very little presence here, and the government did not promote what it considered Western and decadent, like pop or rock. This only started to change in the 1970s and 80s. Jazz was not frowned upon though, I think, so it may have been more popular then than it is now - simply because it was one of fewer options that are available today.

As for you finding good jazz in Poland - with democracy, free expression, market economy, etc., we have pretty much everything here, which must include jazz.

